<font color="#FF0000">I FEEL SHAME</font><br>
<tt>Sat Nov 30  1:55:22 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Like John Ratliff, I wanted a choice and I too, joined the Air Force.  It was 1968. The draft lottery wasn't in effect yet, so the Army and Marine Corp were grabbing 18 and 19 year old kids like crazy (if you didn't have some kind of deferment).  I knew I was't going to college and with a 1-A draft classification, no one would give me a decent job.  <br><br>
I thought I'd be smart see.  I never dreamed by joining the Air Force I've ever been sent to Viet Nam.  Shoot, 7 months after signing on the dotted line, I was there.  My job was to radio air strike targets to fighter air craft and to act as the ground contact for AF forward air controllers (FAC's).  I enjoyed my job.  Heck, after little over a year back in the states, I volunteered for a second tour.    <br><br>
Sometimes I feel guilty for taking the easy way out, but I figure I'd have been a coward out in the field and got someone else killed trying to cover my butt.<br><br>
That's the main reason I never joined any veterans organizations.  I felt too ashamed to associate with real soldiers.
